	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Jamaican cocoa farmers seeking to improve returns by direct marketing</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Jamaica is seeking to diversify the destination of its cocoa exports beyond France, Belgium, Spain and Switzerland, according to press reports. In March 2011, Jamaica Cocoa Farmers’ Association (JCFA) signed a contract with American company Hershey to supply cocoa for the production of its high-end brands. The Hershey deal includes the provision of technical assistance to Jamaican farmers, to improve their capacity ‘to ferment and dry their cocoa beans to maximise the farm-gate returns’. Jamaica is seen as having some of the best cocoa in the world, but only produces a small volume – reaching a maximum of 768 tonnes in 2007.</p><p>The Jamaican press reported that cocoa was ‘now selling within a band of US$3,600 to US$3,700 (J$310,000 to J$318,000) per metric tonne’, yielding farm-gate prices from the Cocoa Board of ‘J$14,600 per metric tonne ... less than five per cent of what the commodity fetches from overseas buyers’. JCFA’s Operations Manager Lorenzo Buckley argued that Jamaican producers must seek to exploit the growing trend towards high-quality chocolate consumption. Currently only 700 of Jamaica’s 11,000 cocoa farmers are members of the JCFA.</p><p>JCFA’s commercial contract with Hershey was facilitated through a USAID-funded programme aimed at improving the marketing and competitiveness of Jamaican agricultural production. This programme has helped JCFA to build its capacity in production and marketing. In addition, JCFA is now seeking to secure ‘a cocoa dealer’s licence’, so that it can trade on its own behalf: currently the Cocoa Industry Board is ‘the only entity engaged in the exporting of beans’ for Jamaica. It is hoped that securing a cocoa dealer’s licence ‘will result in increasing the farm-gate prices’.</p><p>On 1 March 2011 the International Cocoa Organization (ICCO) released its first forecasts for cocoa production in 2010/11 and the revised figures for 2009/10. It shows production rising 8% in the coming year, with a 7.2% increase in end-of-season stocks.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
