				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Approximately 5% of cocoa production consists of fine-flavoured cocoa. Small-scale producers in the Caribbean (Jamaica, Guyana, Belize, Trinidad &amp; Tobago) may find commercial advantages in targeting these speciality markets for cocoa. However, this may require investments in improving the quality of cocoa produced, the establishment of clearly defined and recognisable quality standards and the development of closer ties with end users serving quality-conscious components of the final product market (e.g. high-end chocolate manufacturers).</p><p>However given the small scale and fragmented nature of production, targeted programmes of assistance may be required to assist regional producers in successfully repositioning themselves within global cocoa markets. Such programmes could draw on the experience of the EDF-financed regional Caribbean rum programme, which sought to reposition Caribbean rum producers within evolving global spirits markets. However, any such initiative would from the outset also need to build up an effective dialogue with end users producing high-quality chocolate products. Lessons could be drawn from the ongoing initiative from which the JFCA currently benefits. Such programmes could also consider approaching the current EU-financed Caribbean Fine Cocoa Forum project (budget €780,120) which is currently under implementation.</p>
		</div>
		
